	annote = {In general, the main objectives pursued by water tariffs are
1) economic efficiency,
(2) water conservation incentives,
3) equity, and
(4) affordability
 
in several cases, tariff related policies to insure affordability have led to a tariff structure that does not satisfy economic efficiency or generates water conservation incentives.
the objective of this study is to design a water rate model that internalizes the scarcity value of water, and at the same time is considered fair and equitable by end users.
 
UVC - Uniform Volumetric charge -{\textgreater} no incentive to consevation
IBT - e -{\textgreater}  incentive to consevation + equity (equity by allowing for cross-subsidization between poor residential customers and wealthy households )
* but tend to be poorly designed (upper consumption blocks are not priced at sufficiently high levels and/or because the first consumption block is so large that almost all residential consumers only consume in that level) / penalize arge househods
* critical setting the first block right
    Essential Minimum Quantity (EMQ) - WHO individual's indoor needs for “drinking, cooking, personal washing and washing clothes which is 40 L per person per day”.
 
The proposed water rate is based on the following idea:RFB + RSB =CRUR + ERs +ERWS
 
RFB and RSB represent total perceived revenue from the first and second block, respectively, CRUR is the current revenue received under the uniform rate tariff structure, ERs represents the required extra revenue to cover subsidy costs, and ERWS is the additional revenue due to the increased tariff to signal water scarcity.
 
},
